uhcs

code accompanying 'Exploring the microstructure manifold: image texture representations applied to ultrahigh carbon steel microstructures'. [arxiv.org](http://arxiv.org/abs/1702.01117)

This paper compares SIFT-based image representations with convolutional neural network representations for complex microstructures found in ultrahigh carbon steels.
The micrographs were collected by Matt Hecht at CMU through two studies: [a network morphology study](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?oi=bibs&cluster=16995291491472547776&btnI=1&hl=en) and a spheroidite morphology study (accepted for publication in Met Trans A).

## workflow
unpack dataset (microstructures.sqlite, micrographs/*.{tif,png,jpg}, etc)

# pre-crop micrographs
python scripts/crop_micrographs.py

# generate json files mapping image keys to file paths
# for inertia reasons...
python scripts/enumerate_dataset.py

# compute microstructure representations
# launches a bunch of slurm jobs
# representations stored in hdf5 at data/${format}/features/${representation}.h5
bash scripts/compute_representations.sh

# svm experiments
# data/${format}/svm/${representation}.json
# primary microconstituent:
bash scripts/svm_result.sh

# annealing condition:
bash scripts/sample_svm.sh

# run t-SNE (or other dimensionality reduction method...)
# data/${format}/tsne/${representation}.json
bash tsne_embed.sh
(bash manifold_embed.sh)

# make t-SNE figures
# data/${format}/tsne/${representation}.png
bash tsne_map.sh

# make plots (jupyter....)